“The current tightness of the market looks real,” Doug Porter, chief economist at Bank of Montreal, said in a note. “As a result, we expect some further upward pressure on prices in coming months, and some further upward pressure on household debt to flow from that.”New listings in Canada were down 1.8 per cent in December and are 8% below the 2019 high reached in April, while the sales-to-new listings ratio is the highest since 2004, CREA reported. The ratio for Ottawa hit a record in December, while in Montreal it climbed to the highest since 2003.Barring an unforeseen change in recent trends, “price gains appear poised to accelerate in 2020,” CREA officials said in the statement.The dwindling supply is boosting prices and curtailing overall transactions. The national benchmark price rose 0.8 per cent in December, climbing for a seventh straight month, a period over which home values have increased almost 5 per cent. Home sales, meanwhile, fell last month for the first time since February, extending a recent slowdown.Sales in Toronto dropped 3 per cent in December, with new listings in that market down 5.7 per cent.Even with the recent slowdown, national home sales for all of 2019 rose 6.5 per cent from the previous year, reflecting stronger demand from lower interest rates, a strong labour market and rising population. Still, sales remain well below their 2016 peak.Bloomberg.com
